          "body": "The transition to the dedication ceremony begins with an active search: the Levites were 'sought out from all their places, to bring them to Jerusalem' (v. 27). The singers had built villages around Jerusalem specifically to be near their ministry (vv. 28-29), yet even they had to be gathered. The verb 'sought out' (baqash) implies that the assembly of worshipers for the dedication was not automatic or assumed — it required deliberate effort by the community's leadership. Before a note was sung or a sacrifice was offered, priests and Levites first purified themselves, then extended that purification to the people, the gates, and the wall (v. 30). The order is theologically precise: leaders are purified before they lead, and the integrity of the worship space is established before the community enters it. Great worship does not happen spontaneously; it is organized, assembled, and consecrated in advance."
