          "body": "Nehemiah's organization of two great thanksgiving choirs walking in opposite directions on top of the wall (vv. 31-40) is one of the most architecturally and theologically rich scenes in the book. The choice to walk the wall itself — not merely to process through the streets — is significant. The wall is the object being dedicated; walking it in worship consecrates its entire circumference to God. Every gate that had been rubble and is now rebuilt (chapter 3) becomes a waypoint in a song of praise. The right-hand choir passes the Refuse Gate — the gate of waste and shame — on its way to the house of God; the left-hand choir covers the northern and western perimeter, passing each tower and gate in sequence. When both choirs converge at the house of God (v. 40), the spatial argument is made: all the city's renewed boundaries point toward the temple. The wall that protects Jerusalem is itself under God's sovereignty, offered back to him in song."
