          "body": "The chapter does not end with the celebration of verse 43. It turns immediately to administrative provision: men appointed over storerooms for contributions, firstfruits, and tithes (v. 44), gatekeepers performing purification service (v. 45), and all Israel giving daily portions to singers and gatekeepers (v. 47). The move from ceremony to provision is not an anticlimax — it is the argument that the extraordinary day of joy requires an ordinary system of support. Worship that has no daily provision collapses; the singers who were gathered from their villages for the dedication (v. 27) will return to those villages unless the community funds their presence. The explanatory chain in verses 44-47 is precise: Judah rejoiced over the priests and Levites who served (v. 44), because they performed right worship (v. 45), because David and Solomon had established it (vv. 45-46), and therefore all Israel gave the required portions (v. 47). Joy over God's servants generates the tithes that sustain those servants. The book of Nehemiah ends not on the high note of the ceremony but on the quiet note of 'as each day required' — which is, in its own way, a greater testimony of faith."
